COMPANY PAGE POST:
Cost blowouts on club redevelopments aren't bad luck — they're bad planning.

After years of seeing clubs struggle with budget overruns, the pattern is clear. The biggest cost drivers aren't construction price increases or unforeseen site conditions. They're decisions made (or avoided) before ground is even broken.

Take concept costing. Too many clubs commission beautiful architect renders, get member approval, then discover the budget is 30% short. By then, expectations are locked in and the board is managing a political crisis instead of a design problem.

Or staging. Keeping the club operational during construction isn't optional, but it's expensive. Temporary walls, service diversions, phased demolition — when these aren't considered until tender stage, they hit budgets like a freight train.

The frustrating part? Every one of these cost drivers is preventable with the right approach. Independent costing from day one. Staging as a design constraint, not an afterthought. Proper governance around contingency and variations.

It's not about adding layers of bureaucracy. It's about giving boards the financial transparency they need to make informed decisions.

I've written about the five most common budget killers and how clubs can avoid them. Worth a read if your board is considering a redevelopment.
